  "prompt": "Non-traditional (older students) who went to law school: what was your motivation? Do you regret going (because of student loans)?",
  "response": "I'll help summarize typical responses from non-traditional law students based on various online forums and discussions:\n\nMotivations often include:\n1. Career change\n2. Long-term career aspiration\n3. Personal passion for law/justice\n4. Desire for intellectual challenge\n5. Wanting more meaningful work\n6. Professional advancement\n7. Mid-life career pivot\n\nRegret factors frequently mentioned:\n1. High student loan debt\n2. Opportunity cost of lost earning years\n3. Competitive job market\n4. Challenging work-life balance\n5. Lower starting salaries than expected\n\nGenerally positive perspectives often note:\n- Intellectual satisfaction\n- Personal achievement\n- New skill development\n- Networking opportunities\n- Potential for meaningful work\n\nCaveats typically include:\n- Research job market thoroughly\n- Consider total cost carefully\n- Have realistic expectations\n- Consider part-time/evening programs\n- Explore scholarship/funding options\n\nThese perspectives come from aggregated discussions, not a single source. Individual experiences vary widely.\n\nWould you be interested in hearing more specific anecdotes or detailed perspectives from non-traditional law students?",
